Section section_01 (Chars 0–9137):
Section Summary: The author's interest in science was sparked by reading Tyndall's "Discourse on The Scientific Use of the Imagination" and was further developed by reading Herbert Spencer's works, particularly his essay "Progress: its Law and Cause". Spencer's philosophy of evolution, which describes the transformation of the simple into the complex through successive differentiations, had a profound impact on the author. The author notes that Spencer's idea of differentiation as the cardinal law of evolution implies a universal cause, and that every active force produces more than one change. Spencer's work, although sometimes narrow in focus, made significant contributions to biology, psychology, sociology, and ethics, and his ideas have been widely assimilated into modern scientific thought. The author believes that Spencer's early essay contains the germ of his best teachings and that his method was most effectively employed in interpreting phenomena from a biological or quasi-biological point of view.
