Section section_02 (Chars 9138–12774):
Section Summary: In his later years, Spencer was disheartened to see that his social and political doctrines were not widely accepted by a new generation of thinkers. Despite this, his philosophy of life and mind remains a significant contribution to history. Spencer's philosophy emphasizes the universality of law and evolution, and he believed that all phenomena can be explained in terms of matter, motion, and force. His philosophy is all-inclusive, encompassing biology, psychology, sociology, and ethics as part of the larger mechanical drama of evolution. Ultimately, Spencer's philosophy acknowledges the mystery of existence, but seeks to explain everything in terms of the interrelationship between matter and mind.
